\section{Beyond the Schwinger Model}

%------------------------------------------------
\begin{frame}{Beyond the Schwinger Model: Why Move Forward?}

The Schwinger model (1+1D QED):

\begin{itemize}
\item Abelian
\item No transverse gauge dynamics
\item Gauge fields can be eliminated
\end{itemize}

But realistic gauge theories (e.g. QCD) are:

\begin{itemize}
\item Non-Abelian
\item Higher dimensional (3+1D)
\item Dynamically rich
\end{itemize}

Key question:
\[
\text{Can quantum simulation scale beyond 1+1D Abelian theories?}
\]
\end{frame}

%------------------------------------------------
\begin{frame}{Non-Abelian Gauge Theories on Quantum Hardware}

Progress beyond U(1):

\begin{itemize}
\item SU(2) lattice gauge theories in 1+1D
\item Small SU(3) toy models
\item Finite-dimensional truncations of gauge fields
\end{itemize}

New challenges:

\begin{itemize}
\item Self-interacting gauge bosons
\item Larger local Hilbert spaces
\item More complex Gauss-law constraints
\end{itemize}

Status: proof-of-principle demonstrations and classical circuit simulations.
\end{frame}

%------------------------------------------------
\begin{frame}{Higher Dimensions: 2+1D and Beyond}

Moving to 2+1 dimensions introduces:

\begin{itemize}
\item Plaquette terms:
\[
U_p = \mathrm{Tr}(U_1 U_2 U_3^\dagger U_4^\dagger)
\]
\item Genuine magnetic field dynamics
\item Multi-qubit interactions
\end{itemize}

Scaling challenge:

\[
\text{Gate depth} \sim N_{\text{sites}}^2 \text{ or worse}
\]

Only small lattices currently feasible.
\end{frame}

%------------------------------------------------
\begin{frame}{Quantum Link Models (QLMs)}

Conceptual advance:

Replace infinite-dimensional gauge links with
finite-dimensional spin representations.

\[
U_{ij} \rightarrow \text{spin operators}
\]

Advantages:

\begin{itemize}
\item Finite local Hilbert space
\item Hardware-friendly
\item Gauge invariance encoded locally
\end{itemize}

Actively explored in:

\begin{itemize}
\item Trapped ions
\item Rydberg atoms
\item Cold atom optical lattices
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}

%------------------------------------------------
\begin{frame}{Analog Quantum Simulators}

Parallel development:

\begin{itemize}
\item Z$_2$ lattice gauge theories
\item U(1) gauge invariance
\item Small SU(2) systems
\end{itemize}

Analog platforms:

\begin{itemize}
\item Ultracold atoms
\item Rydberg arrays
\item Trapped ions
\end{itemize}

In some cases, analog simulation has surpassed digital NISQ hardware.
\end{frame}

%------------------------------------------------
\begin{frame}{Where Do We Stand?}

Current frontier:

\begin{itemize}
\item Schwinger model: mature benchmark
\item SU(2) in 1+1D: active research
\item 2+1D U(1): small systems
\item Quantum link models: promising
\end{itemize}

Still missing:

\begin{itemize}
\item 3+1D SU(3) QCD on quantum hardware
\item Continuum-limit extrapolation
\item Fault-tolerant large-scale simulations
\end{itemize}

We are in the \textbf{proof-of-principle era}.
\end{frame}

%================================================
\section{Conclusions}

%------------------------------------------------
\begin{frame}{Conclusions}

\begin{itemize}
\item Lattice gauge theories encode nonperturbative physics.
\item Quantum computers simulate Hamiltonian dynamics directly.
\item State preparation is the central challenge.
\item Scaling to continuum remains open.
\end{itemize}

Quantum simulation of gauge theories is promising but technically demanding.
\end{frame}

